<!--
  ★ HERO — your one-line hook + bio. The reader should know what you do in under 5 seconds.

  GUIDANCE FOR WRITING YOUR HOOK (especially if your experience is sparse or spans different areas):

  • Lead with verbs you actually enjoy doing, not job titles you don't have yet.
    "I design, write, and overthink coffee" beats "Aspiring UX Designer & Generalist."

  • If your experiences span different domains, name the COMMON THREAD instead of listing fields.
    A common thread can be a question ("what makes something feel cared for?"),
    a perspective ("designing for people who don't fit a standard mold"),
    or an approach ("I start every project by listening, then sketching").

  • If your experiences are in DIFFERENT categories, group them honestly.
    Three buckets work well: "Design + Research + Writing" or "Visual + Service + Systems"
    or "Code + Craft + Storytelling." Categories are clearer than vague generalist claims.

  • If you're early-career, "designer/builder/student of X" is honest and works.
    "Student of taste, working in product design and community organizing."

  PICK THREE VERBS THAT ARE TRUE. Specific verbs always beat generic ones.
  Strong: "I cook, design, and write." / "I draw, code, and run things."
  Weak:   "I create, innovate, and ideate."
-->
<header class="hero" id="top">
  <div class="wrap">
    <h1 class="hook">
      I design <em>{{verb 1}}</em>, {{verb 2}} &amp; {{verb 3}}.
    </h1>
    <p class="bio">
      {{Your one-paragraph bio. ~2-4 sentences.}}
      <!--
        SUGGESTED SHAPE (when experience feels sparse or scattered):

        Sentence 1 — WHO YOU ARE in the most honest, specific way.
          Role (or "student of"), location, 1 thing that orients your work.
          Example: "I'm a student of design at Dartmouth, focused on how mundane objects shape behavior."

        Sentence 2 — WHAT KINDS OF PROBLEMS pull you in.
          Pick a slice — a population, a domain, or a quality.
          Example: "I'm most curious about things that get used every day but rarely get redesigned."

        Sentence 3 (optional) — HOW you work or who you do your best work with.
          Example: "I do my best work alongside people who care about the small details."

        Skip the buzzwords. "User-centric paradigms" reads weaker than "I talk to people first."

        Gloria Lo's version for reference:
        "Product designer based in Sydney, Australia with experience in delivering end-to-end UX/UI design."
      -->
    </p>
  </div>
</header>

